;; === hot_swap_test.aura ===
;;
;; Test the hot-swap:fn primitive.
;;
;; === STATUS ===
;;
;; hot-swap:fn is implemented in the evaluator as a primitive that calls
;; into the CompilerService's hot-swap callback. The callback:
;;   1. Parses the new source
;;   2. Lowers it to IR
;;   3. Looks for a function with the given name in the IR module
;;   4. Calls IRModule::hot_swap_function to replace it in place
;;
;; === CURRENT LIMITATION ===
;;
;; The hot-swap works ONLY for functions that have a corresponding
;; entry in IRModule::functions[]. In Aura's typical lowering:
;;   - (define (greet n) ...) → __lambda__ (the inner lambda gets this name)
;;   - top-level expression → __top__
;;
;; So the user-supplied name "greet" is NOT in IRModule::functions[].
;; To find the function by its user-visible name, the runtime would need
;; to walk the env to find the cell, then read the closure's func_id.
;; This is a TODO for the tree-walker path.
;;
;; === TESTS (these verify the primitive exists and behaves as expected) ===

;; Test 1: primitive exists
(display (procedure? hot-swap:fn)) (newline)  ; #t

;; Test 2: wrong arg count returns #f
(display (hot-swap:fn)) (newline)  ; #f
(display (hot-swap:fn "x")) (newline)  ; #f

;; Test 3: non-string arg returns #f
(display (hot-swap:fn 42 "x")) (newline)  ; #f

;; Test 4: non-existent function (in tree-walker path) returns #f
(display (hot-swap:fn "nonexistent" "(define (nonexistent) 42)")) (newline)  ; #f
